        "trailText":"Ten thousand people march past the Cenotaph in central London as Queen and politicians pay tribute to Britain's war dead",
        "headline":"Remembrance Sunday marked by silent tributes across the world",
        "body":"<p>In brilliant autumn sunshine, and the lengthening shadow of the approaching centenary of the war to end all wars, the pavements were lined 10-deep on Whitehall long before the start of the Remembrance Sunday ceremony.</p><p>When the  street was officially declared \"at capacity\" by the police, with 10,000 people lined up waiting to march past the Cenotaph once the Queen and the politicians had laid their wreaths, crowds were still piling into Parliament and Trafalgar squares  to be present when the deep boom of a first world war field gun launched the eerie silence at the heart of the capital. Many brought small children, who almost without exception – a single hastily stifled wail was just audible on Whitehall – were awed into joining the silence.</p><p>The two-minute tribute, originally intended, like the Cenotaph – first built as a temporary wooden structure – as a gesture of mourning and remembrance just for November 1919 when the slaughter of the war was still agonisingly close,  has been repeated every year,  in ceremonies  in towns and cities and at modest village war memorials, across Britain and overseas.</p><p>With the deaths in the past decade of the last veterans of the first world war, it was thought the event might dwindle to a small official ceremony: instead it seems to grow every year.</p><p>This year, the parade, which took well over an hour to pass the Cenotaph, was led by the War Widows Association: some shockingly young faces demonstrated why remembering those who die in war has never gone out of fashion.</p><p>In Ireland, the taoiseach, Enda Kenny, travelled north of the border to  join the Northern Ireland secretary, Theresa Villiers, in laying wreaths at the memorial in Enniskillen, in the heart of the town ripped apart by an IRA bomb during a Remembrance ceremony 26 years ago, killing 11 people. His deputy, Eamon Gilmore, attended the ceremony in Belfast.</p><p>Prince Andrew and the defence secretary, Philip Hammond, laid their wreaths at Camp Bastion in Helmand province in Afghanistan, where 446 British personnel have died since 2001. The prince said Remembrance Sunday brought back personal memories of  friends and colleagues  lost in the Falklands. \"I always think of those I served with, who never came back,\" he said.</p><p>At Wootton Bassett in Wiltshire, people stood in silence again, in the streets  where for years the bustle of everyday life stopped  every time repatriated bodies, 345 in all, were driven through the town from the nearby airfield.</p><p>One group of 60  British schoolchildren aged between nine and 18 travelled to Ypres, where they will join in the ceremony at the Menin Gate on Monday  for the actual 11 November anniversary.  Twinned with Belgian schools who are hosting them, they are also collecting soil from battlefields in Flanders, which will be brought back to create a memorial garden next year at Wellington Barracks, near Buckingham Palace.</p><p>A wreath was laid at the Cenotaph by Prince Harry on behalf of his father, who attended a ceremony at a Commonwealth War Graves cemetery at Kirkee, in India, where he and his wife were shown the graves of the youngest and oldest buried there, 15-year-old bandsman Norman Halliburn, and 68-year-old Sydney Frankcom, who both died in the 1940s as the Japanese advanced through Burma. They also met a group of second world war veterans at the \"Afghan\" church in Mumbai – built not to mark the present but the many who died in the 19th-century war.</p><p>In Whitehall, a large delegation  from the Korean Veterans Association joined the parade for the last time.  The war, which cost the lives of 1,139 British service personnel,   seems painfully recent to many although this year marks the 60th anniversary of the armistice that ended it – leaving the still gaping fault line between North and South Korea. Although individuals will join future ceremonies, the veterans association is being dissolved because most of the survivors are now in their 80s.</p><p>One small group joined the parade for the first time, nondescript now, their wartime activities entirely unknown to their families in 1942.  The activities of the Auxiliary Units, known as \"Churchill's Secret Army\", were kept so quiet, with each unit operating in isolation, that Trevor Miners, from Perranporth, who has been campaigning to win them official recognition, has no means of contacting many of the veterans who signed the Official Secrets Act during the war, and in many cases have never broken it since. They never saw active service, but their intended role was to surface as secret agents, sabotaging and harrying the enemy, after a German invasion.</p><p>The parade, including a loudly cheered group of Gurkhas, marched briskly without registering another small group of Gurkhas who have been mounting a vigil at the feet of the towering statue of Monty, Field Marshall Viscount Montgomery, for the past fortnight. Some have launched a hunger strike there as part of their campaign for better pensions, medical treatment and settlement rights for Gurkha veterans and their families.</p><p>Nearby, peace campaigner Maria Galliastegui, a veteran of the camp set up by Brian Haw and others on Parliament Square, stood wearing a white poppy. She had met with no antagonism but little recognition for the gesture, she said.</p><p>\"This is a very moving event. You have to honour all the people who have served this country and given up their lives on our behalf.  But we have got to re-awaken the peace movement. We have got to ensure that the politicians bring the troops home by next year – and not just leave us strategically positioned for wars to come in Syria and Iran.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/422126015|2013-11-11T15:34:05Z|2eea10e0581a8134484398d8c38b06f04e5d5cd2 -->",
